Let $A$ be the matrix above. We apply this matrix to points in  $S$. Therefore $AX=B$ where A is the given matrix and X represents some vector i.e. $\begin{pmatrix}x \\ y \end{pmatrix}.$ Thus, we solve for this equation as follows , 
\begin{align*}
A_X &=AX \\ 
\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 1 \\ 7 & -3 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix}x \\ y \end{pmatrix} &= \begin{pmatrix}2x+y\\ 7x-3y\end{pmatrix}\\ 
\end{align*}
As this matrix represents each coordinate from two lines(where x and y values) we multiply $B$ by the matrix $A$ by multiplying each column of A with $B$ i.e. the product from right to left. Our purpose is to find the area  of $S'$ represented by B where $B = AX.$
\begin{align*} 
\begin{pmatrix}2x+y\\ 7x-3y\end{pmatrix} &=\begin{pmatrix}2(10) +1(10)\\ 7(10) -3(10)\end{pmatrix}\hspace{10pt}\text{Since this matrix is of dimensions is 2 x 2 and A is our scale factor} \\ &=  \begin{pmatrix}30\\ 40\end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}
Here we can see that our region $S$ obtained upon multiplication of $A$ by ten goes from a length of 10 to a length of 30 which would make the sides ten times larger. Similarly, $S$ from the y-axis spans a distance of 10 on the y-axis. In doing so, the ranges on the $x$ and $y axis$ from $S$ to $S'$ stretch abnormally more due to the scale factor applied here on $S$. As the scaling has happened in all directions, the length of the side on the $x$ axis had to shrink. Conversely, the length on the $y$ axis had to grow away from the origin. Thus the bim perimeters of our regions $S$ and $S'$ infinitely shrink away from the origin. However, the perimeter of $S' =  2x + 2y$, where we were already familiar that $40 = 2x + 20 = 2x + y$ and $30 = 7x-3y$. Thus simplifying this by division by two, we get $20 = x + 10 = x + y$ and $15 = \frac{7x}{2} -\frac{3y}{2}$. This gives us $$40 = \begin{pmatrix} 2 & 1 \\ 7 & -3 \end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}10 \\ 10 \end{pmatrix}$$ Now the answer is $$\textrm{det} \begin{pmatrix}2 & 1 \\7 & -3 \end{pmatrix}=\boxed{-13}$$</answer>

